<body><p>GE.12-12136  (E)    200312    200312 
</p>
<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Nineteenth session 
</b>Agenda item 10 
<b>Technical assistance and capacity-building 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Senegal (on behalf of the African Group): draft resolution 
</b></p>
<p><b>  19/&#8230; 
Draft resolution on the human rights situation in the Democratic 
Republic of the Congo and the strengthening of technical cooperation 
and advisory services 
</b></p>
<p> <i>The Human Rights Council</i>, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling </i>General Assembly resolution 60/251 of 15 March 2006, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling also</i> Council resolutions 5/1 of 18 June 2007, 7/20 of 27 March 2008 and 
S-8/1 of 1 December 2008, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recalling</i> <i>further </i>Council resolution 10/33 of 27 March 2009, in which the Council 
called on the international community to support the establishment of a local cooperation 
mechanism by the Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo and the 
international community, referred to as the human rights liaison entity, 
</p>
<p> <i>Taking</i> <i>into account</i> Council resolution 13/22 of 26 March 2010, in which the 
Council requested the Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo to develop an 
action plan with specific timelines for the implementation of recommendations on human 
rights, particularly regarding the fight against impunity, 
</p>
<p> <i>Also recalling</i> Council resolution 16/35 of 25 March 2011, in which the Council 
called upon the international community to support the national efforts of the Democratic 
Republic of the Congo and its institutions with a view to improving the human rights 
situation in the country, and to respond to its requests for technical assistance, 
</p>
<p> <i>Reaffirming</i> that all States have an obligation to promote and protect human rights 
and fundamental freedoms, as stated in the Charter of the United Nations, the Universal 
Declaration of Human Rights, the International Covenants on Human Rights and other 
applicable instruments to which they are parties, 
</p>
<p> <i>Noting with concern</i> the human rights situation in the Democratic Republic of the 
Congo, mainly in the eastern part of the country, resulting from abuse committed by foreign 
and national armed groups opposing the peace process, and calling upon the Government to 
ensure respect for human rights and international humanitarian law, 
</p>
<p> United Nations A/HRC/19/L.15
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>General Assembly </b>Distr.: Limited 
16 March 2012 
English 
Original: French </p>


<p><b>2</b> GE.12-12136 
</p>
<p> <i>Strongly supporting</i> the efforts of the Government of the Democratic Republic of the 
Congo to put an end to the cycle of impunity for grave international crimes by 
strengthening its justice system, 
 <i>Noting with concern</i> cases of electoral and sexual violence, and noting with 
appreciation the progress made by the authorities of the Democratic Republic of the Congo 
in following up on the conviction of perpetrators and the provision of reparations to 
victims,  
</p>
<p> <i>Acknowledging</i> the joint role played by the Office of the United Nations High 
Commissioner for human rights in the Democratic Republic of the Congo and the human 
rights section of the United Nations Organization Stabilization Mission in the Democratic 
Republic of the Congo in improving the human rights situation in the country, 
</p>
<p> <i>Recognizing</i> the existence of a national programme for the promotion and protection 
of human rights in the Democratic Republic of the Congo and the resolve of the 
Government to implement it, 
</p>
<p> <i>Noting</i> the decision by the National Independent Electoral Commission to continue 
organizing elections at the provincial and local levels, 
</p>
<p> <i>Considering</i> the presence of the Joint Committee on Justice as a framework for the 
partners to exchange ideas and coordinate their activities related to justice in the 
Democratic Republic of the Congo, 
</p>
<p> <i>Noting </i>the report on the situation of human rights in the Democratic Republic of the 
Congo presented by the Government, which addresses in particular judicial monitoring of 
the electoral process, the creation of domestically established follow-up mechanisms for 
human rights and the implementation of the action plan for implementation of 
recommendations relating to human rights, 
</p>
<p> <i>Noting also</i> the report of the High Commissioner on the human rights situation in 
the Democratic Republic of the Congo and the activities of her Office in the country, 
</p>
<p> 1. <i>Takes note</i> of the commitment of the Government of the Democratic 
Republic of the Congo to cooperate with the Office of the United Nations High 
Commissioner for Human Rights in the Democratic Republic of the Congo and with the 
special procedures of the Human Rights Council;  
</p>
<p> 2. <i>Thanks</i> the Government in this regard for hosting the visit to the country 
from 25 July to 5 August 2011 of the independent expert on the effects of foreign debt and 
other related international financial obligations of States on the full enjoyment of all human 
rights, particularly economic, social and cultural rights; 
</p>
<p> 3. <i>Encourages </i>the Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo to 
ensure that the human rights liaison entity is able to act as a framework for consultation and 
coordination on human rights in the country, and <i>approves</i> of the extension of that body to 
the provinces so as to ensure local monitoring of the human rights situation; 
</p>
<p> 4. <i>Commends</i> the role played by the international community, in particular the 
European Union, the African Union, the Southern African Development Community, the 
Economic Community of the Great Lakes Countries and the Economic Community of 
Central African States, in supporting the efforts of the Democratic Republic of the Congo to 
strengthen the rule of law and improve the human rights situation in the country; 
</p>
<p> 5. <i>Urges </i>the Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo to redouble 
its efforts, with the support of the international community, to expeditiously put an end to 
all violations of human rights and bring perpetrators to justice;  </p>


<p>GE.12-12136 <b>3 
</b></p>
<p> 6. <i>Welcomes</i> the efforts of the Government of the Democratic Republic of the 
Congo to put an end to all human rights violations and to assist victims of such violations; 
</p>
<p> 7. <i>Welcomes</i> the holding on 28 November 2011 of the second democratic and 
free presidential and legislative elections in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, and 
<i>encourages</i> the newly elected authorities to ensure that the population&#8217;s living conditions 
improve; 
</p>
<p> 8. <i>Invites</i> the international community to continue to support the Joint 
Committee on Justice as a framework for the exchange of ideas and coordination of the 
various contributions related to justice in the Democratic Republic of the Congo; 
 9. <i>Welcomes also</i> the fact that the Government of the Democratic Republic of 
the Congo has adopted and sent to the Senate bills on the protection of human rights 
defenders and on the establishment of a specialized court to hear cases involving grave 
violations of human rights and international humanitarian law, and <i>encourages</i> it to strive 
for the quick adoption by the new national Parliament of these instruments; 
</p>
<p> 10. <i>Takes note</i> of the initiatives taken by the Government of the Democratic 
Republic of the Congo to promote the administration of justice and human rights, in 
particular by assigning the 2,000 newly recruited magistrates to posts throughout the 
country, by making the juvenile courts operational, by establishing a unit for the protection 
of human rights defenders and by organizing open house events for the protection of 
victims of human rights violations and of abuse of power in the justice system; 
 11. <i>Encourages</i> the Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo to 
continue to ratify international and regional human rights instruments and to promote 
human rights education; 
</p>
<p> 12. <i>Encourages</i> the Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo to 
complete the establishment of a national human rights commission, in accordance with the 
Principles relating to the Status of National Institutions for the Promotion and Protection of 
Human Rights (the Paris Principles); 
 13. <i>Invites </i>the Office of the High Commissioner, through its presence in the 
Democratic Republic of the Congo, to increase and enhance its technical assistance 
programmes and activities requested by the Government; 
</p>
<p> 14. <i>Calls upon</i> the international community to support the national efforts of the 
Democratic Republic of the Congo and its institutions with a view to improving the human 
rights situation in the country, and to respond to its requests for technical assistance. 
</p>
<p>    </p>

